---
import ToolPage from '../layouts/ToolPage.astro';
import PromptTool from '../components/PromptTool.tsx';
import PromptToolLinks from '../components/PromptToolLinks.astro';
---

<ToolPage
  title="LLM Request Inspector — Format OpenAI & Claude Logs"
  description="Inspect OpenAI and Claude request logs in your browser. Split system, user, assistant and tool messages, unescape prompt text and pretty-print nested JSON."
  h1="LLM Request Inspector"
  intro="Paste the final OpenAI or Claude request from your application log and see what the model actually received: ordered message roles, tool calls, restored line breaks and readable nested JSON. Processing stays in your browser."
  path="/prompt"
  faq={[
    {
      q: 'Does it work with ChatGPT / OpenAI prompts?',
      a: 'Yes. It recognizes common role labels used by ChatGPT, Claude and other LLM APIs.',
    },
    {
      q: 'Is anything sent to a server?',
      a: 'No — formatting runs entirely in your browser, so prompts stay private.',
    },
    {
      q: 'What input formats can I paste?',
      a: 'You can paste plain prompt text, escaped log output, role-labeled conversations, JSON message arrays and request payloads that contain prompt text.',
    },
    {
      q: 'Does formatting change what the model received?',
      a: 'The formatter creates a readable view for inspection. Always compare the formatted result with the original log before reusing it as an exact API payload.',
    },
    {
      q: 'Can it find secrets in a prompt log?',
      a: 'It warns about several common token, private-key and email patterns and can copy a redacted draft, but automated detection is incomplete. Review every message and tool result before sharing.',
    },
  ]}
>
  <PromptTool client:only="react" />

  <Fragment slot="content">
    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Why format a prompt?</h2>
    <p class="mt-2">
      When you copy a prompt out of logs or an API request it's often a single escaped line —
      <code>\n</code> instead of real line breaks, JSON crammed inline, and system/user/assistant
      turns run together. This tool untangles all of that so the prompt is actually readable while you
      debug.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">What it does</h2>
    <ul class="mt-2 list-disc space-y-1 pl-6">
      <li><strong>Unescape</strong> literal <code>\n</code>, <code>\t</code> and quotes.</li>
      <li><strong>Pretty-print</strong> inline JSON payloads.</li>
      <li><strong>Split roles</strong> — system, user, assistant, tool — onto their own blocks.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">A practical debugging example</h2>
    <p class="mt-2">
      An OpenAI or Anthropic request copied from a log may contain a messages array on one line,
      escaped line breaks inside <code>content</code>, and nested tool arguments stored as a JSON
      string. The formatter separates each role, restores readable whitespace and indents embedded
      objects. That makes it easier to spot a missing system instruction, a duplicated user turn or
      malformed tool arguments without editing the source log first.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">How to inspect a logged prompt safely</h2>
    <ol class="mt-2 list-decimal space-y-2 pl-6">
      <li>Copy the smallest complete request or conversation from your application log.</li>
      <li>Paste it into the formatter and check that the detected role boundaries match the original.</li>
      <li>Review system instructions, user content and tool payloads separately.</li>
      <li>Keep the raw log available: the formatted view is for reading, not a replacement for forensic evidence.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">What the formatter deliberately does not do</h2>
    <p class="mt-2">
      It does not send the prompt to an AI model, judge prompt quality, count model-specific tokens or
      guarantee that reconstructed JSON is byte-for-byte identical to the original request. Secrets
      can still be visible on your screen, so redact API keys and personal data before sharing a
      screenshot or copied result.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Sensitive-data warning and redacted drafts</h2>
    <p class="mt-2">
      When the input resembles a bearer token, common API key, private key or email address, the tool
      displays a local warning. You can copy a redacted draft that replaces those detected patterns,
      but it is only a first pass. Customer text, internal policies, identifiers and tool results still
      require human review. Follow the
      <a class="text-brand-600 underline" href="/guides/redact-secrets-from-prompt-logs/">prompt log redaction checklist</a>
      before sharing a trace.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <h3 class="mt-4 font-semibold text-slate-800">Does it work with ChatGPT / OpenAI prompts?</h3>
    <p class="mt-1">
      Yes. It recognizes common role labels used by ChatGPT, Claude and other LLM APIs.
    </p>
    <h3 class="mt-4 font-semibold text-slate-800">Is anything sent to a server?</h3>
    <p class="mt-1">No — formatting runs entirely in your browser, so prompts stay private.</p>
    <h3 class="mt-4 font-semibold text-slate-800">What input formats can I paste?</h3>
    <p class="mt-1">
      You can paste plain prompt text, escaped log output, role-labeled conversations, JSON message
      arrays and request payloads that contain prompt text.
    </p>
    <h3 class="mt-4 font-semibold text-slate-800">Does formatting change what the model received?</h3>
    <p class="mt-1">
      The formatter creates a readable view for inspection. Always compare the formatted result with
      the original log before reusing it as an exact API payload.
    </p>
    <h3 class="mt-4 font-semibold text-slate-800">Can it find secrets in a prompt log?</h3>
    <p class="mt-1">
      It warns about several common token, private-key and email patterns and can copy a redacted
      draft, but automated detection is incomplete. Review every message and tool result before sharing.
    </p>

    <PromptToolLinks current="/prompt" />
  </Fragment>
</ToolPage>
